      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Divorce Truly a Salvation?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Lane letter disputes Jane Smiley's September 12 Op-Ed article on divorce</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''There They Go, Bad-Mouthing Divorce Again,'' by Jane Smiley (Op-Ed, Sept. 12):</p>
        <p>I agree with Ms. Smiley that divorce is sometimes a good and necessary thing. But the easy availability of divorce and the increasing use of prenuptial agreements seem to have turned marriage into a throwaway, commitment-free arrangement.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''There They Go, Bad-Mouthing Divorce Again,'' by Jane Smiley (Op-Ed, Sept. 12):</p>
        <p>I agree with Ms. Smiley that divorce is sometimes a good and necessary thing. But the easy availability of divorce and the increasing use of prenuptial agreements seem to have turned marriage into a throwaway, commitment-free arrangement.</p>
        <p>Ms. Smiley surveys her world and sees people who should get divorced. I survey my world and see broken relationships that could have been nurturing and loving if only the participants had tried a little harder.</p>
        <p>ROBERT LANE  San Francisco, Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
